  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Written on the Wall of the Government Residence—A Verse Composed While Mounted on a High Mountain
  author: Choe Yeong-yu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In service to the king, I find my way,
    Yet still can seek the beauty of the day.
    Mountain crows cry out from ridge-worn trees,
    Wild ducks drift gently on the flowing breeze.
    A thousand peaks, snow-girdled, worn and thin,
    One winding path leads through the hamlets in.
    When rare and perfect vistas meet my sight,
    I stop my horse and linger there, in light.
  footnotes:
    - The poem celebrates the dual nature of official service—duty to the crown alongside personal freedom to appreciate natural beauty
    - The 'high mountain' setting and the act of composing while traveling on horseback were common romantic tropes in East Asian literati poetry, suggesting both the poet's noble station and his enlightened sensibility
